hshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1130–December 1170":"1130–December 1170","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1125–1170":"1125–1170","1170–1210":"1170–1210","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1152–Male":"1152–Deceased","1154–1220":"1154–1220","–Male":"Deceased","1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Deceased","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","December 1170":"December 1170","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Abt 1104":"about 1104","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Forfarshire, Scotland","Strathearn, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ruthven","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name, traditionally pronounced ‘Ri-ven’, from Ruthven by Huntingtower (Perthshire); also possibly from Ruthven (Angus) and various other places of that name throughout Scotland, named either with Gaelic <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>mhaighin</i> ‘place’ or with a cognate of Welsh <i>rhudd faen</i> ‘red stone’. The oldest family of this name, the lords of the barony of Ruthven by Perth, were descended from Thor, son of Swain, lord of Tranent in Lothian and first sheriff of Edinburgh on record in the mid 12th century. The family eventually gained the title of Earl of Gowrie, but because of what became known as ‘the Gowrie Conspiracy’ the title was forfeited and from 1600 to 1641 the surname itself was proscribed. The title was later restored to the family, and the present Earl of Gowrie bears the surname <i>Ruthven</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ethne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Eithne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Etna","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]},{"name":"Eithne","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from <i>eithne</i> ‘kernel’, which was used as a term of praise in bardic poetry. St Eithne was a daughter of King Laoghaire and one of St Patrick's first converts."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ethne Ruthven was born in 1130, in Ruthven, Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sweyn of Ruthven and Lady Sweyn Ruthven. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Ferquhard Strathearn. She died in December 1170, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1130–December 1170":"1130–detsember 1170","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1125–1170":"1125–1170","1170–1210":"1170–1210","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","1154–1220":"1154–1220","–Male":"Surnud","1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Surnud","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","December 1170":"detsember 1170","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Abt 1104":"umbes 1104","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1125":"1125","1223":"1223","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","Ruthven, Angus, Scotland":"Ruthven, Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ruthven, Forfarshire, Scotland":"Ruthven, Forfarshire, Scotland","Strathearn, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","OF, RUTHVEN, PERTH, SCOTLAND":"Ruthven, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1130–December 1170":"1130–joulukuu 1170","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1125–1170":"1125–1170","1170–1210":"1170–1210","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","1154–1220":"1154–1220","–Male":"Kuollut","1090–1145":"1090–1145","–Female":"Kuollut","1090":"1090","1154":"1154","December 1170":"joulukuu 1170","1220":"1220","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","Abt 1104":"noin 1104","1150":"1150","1170":"1